<?xml version="1.0" standalone="yes"?>
<!DOCTYPE PLUGIN [
<!ENTITY name      "buddynet">
<!ENTITY author    "TZERO78">
<!ENTITY version   "2026.06.20.3">
<!ENTITY launch    "Tools/buddynet">
<!ENTITY gitURL    "https://github.com/TZERO78/buddynet">
<!ENTITY pluginURL "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/TZERO78/buddynet/main/unraid/BuddyNet/buddynet.plg">
<!ENTITY plgPATH   "/boot/config/plugins/&name;">
<!ENTITY emhttp    "/usr/local/emhttp/plugins/&name;">
]>

<PLUGIN name="&name;" author="&author;" version="&version;" launch="&launch;"
        pluginURL="&pluginURL;" min="6.10.0"
        icon="exchange"
        project="https://github.com/TZERO78/buddynet"
        support="https://github.com/TZERO78/buddynet/issues"
        readme="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/TZERO78/buddynet/main/unraid/BuddyNet/README.md">

<CHANGES>
**BuddyNet** — one binary, three roles. On Unraid you run the `buddy` role: a
zero-config, end-to-end-encrypted tunnel to your buddy. It finds your partner via
a small handshake server, hole-punches through NAT (no port forwarding), and
falls back to a blind relay only if a direct path is impossible. Point
rsync/borg/kopia at the local socket and back up directly between two sites — in
either direction over one tunnel. Two buddies is the simplest case; with a
manifest, one node can hold many at once (MultiPeer).

###2026.06.20.3
- Pinned to buddynet **v2.3.0**. Adds a **hard limit of 48 buddies per node** (a
  deliberate design limit for a personal overlay — over-limit manifests are
  refused fail-closed, never silently truncated) plus VIP-collision rejection at
  peer assembly. Hardening: the key file is **refused if it is a symlink** (no
  follow on stat/chmod/write). Relay abuse ceilings are now configurable
  (`--relay-max-sessions` / `--relay-max-legs-per-ip`). The lab-only `--insecure`
  flag was renamed to `--lab` (the plugin never used it; production is unaffected).
  No settings-page or protocol change from v2.2.1. Checksum gate set to the v2.3.0
  `buddynet-linux-amd64` sha256.

###2026.06.20.2
- Pinned to buddynet **v2.2.1** — bug-fix release. Fixes a **re-pair deadlock on
  one-sided session loss** (a one-sided restore-from-backup, or a `peers remove` +
  `peers add` re-invite, no longer strands a buddy): a stale session now falls
  back to the manifest bootstrap token to recover, key stays pinned. Also a
  readable `peers list` and the connection lifecycle in the log schema. No
  settings-page or protocol change from v2.2.0. Checksum gate set to the v2.2.1
  `buddynet-linux-amd64` sha256.

###2026.06.20.1
- Pinned to buddynet **v2.2.0** — security-hardening release. The pairing token
  is now **sealed to the server's key** (no cleartext token on plain UDP), plus
  panic isolation, a lock-free relay, bounded `-forward` streams, enforced key
  perms, an env-gated `--insecure`, and startup VIP reconcile. Checksum gate set
  to the v2.2.0 `buddynet-linux-amd64` sha256.
  - **Breaking control-plane change (protocol 5→6):** the handshake server and
    every buddy must be on v2.2.0 — older nodes will not pair. No data-plane or
    settings-page change.

###2026.06.20
- Pinned to buddynet **v2.1.0** — the binary gains **MultiPeer**: one node can
  hold many buddy tunnels at once (`--peers-file` manifest, `--vip-listen`
  name routing, `buddynet peers list/add/remove`, live reload on `SIGHUP`); one
  failing buddy never affects the others. Checksum gate set to the v2.1.0
  `buddynet-linux-amd64` sha256.
  - The Unraid settings page still drives the single-buddy setup; MultiPeer is
    available from the command line for now. No breaking change — additive on
    the v2.0.0 wire format and virtual IPs.

###2026.06.19.2
- Renamed the `.buddy` name-resolution feature to **BuddyDNS** (settings-page
  labels + docs only; no functional change, same `--name`/`--dns` flags).

###2026.06.19.1
- Pinned to buddynet **v2.0.0** (first release carrying BuddyDNS/Lazy *and* the
  `/16` virtual-IP change). Checksum gate set to the v2.0.0 `buddynet-linux-amd64`
  sha256.
  - **BREAKING:** v2.0.0 widens the virtual IP to `10.66.X.Y` (a `/16`), so every
    node's virtual IP changes — your buddy must **re-pin** your Buddy key after
    the update.

###2026.06.19
- Surfaced **BuddyDNS** and the **Lazy tunnel** on the settings page:
  - **BuddyDNS name** (`--name`) — reachable as `&lt;name&gt;.buddy`.
  - **BuddyDNS resolver** (`--dns`) — answer `*.buddy` on `127.0.0.153:53`
    (runs as root here, so the privileged bind succeeds).
  - **Lazy tunnel** (`--lazy`) — defer the encrypted tunnel until the first `-L`
    connection arrives; ignored (with a log warning) when no `-L` is set.
- MAINTAINER: bump `BINVER`/`BINSHA` to the **v2.0.0** release (the first build
  carrying these features and the `/16` virtual-IP change) before publishing.

###2026.06.15.1
- Pinned to buddynet **v1.2.1** — completes the structured log schema: a
  virtual-IP mismatch now logs `SECURITY: event=vip-mismatch` at the detection
  point (all detection points now emit `SECURITY:` events). Checksum gate bumped
  to the v1.2.1 `buddynet-linux-amd64` sha256.

###2026.06.15
- Pinned to buddynet **v1.2.0** (security hardening + structured logging release):
  - Relay return-routability cookie, open-mode proof-of-possession, and
    token-squat / intrusion detection on the handshake server.
  - Unified, security-aware log schema (`SECURITY:` / state transitions /
    per-minute stats with `ALERT`). The buddy now tags its journal lines with
    `SyslogIdentifier=buddynet-buddy@<name>` for per-tunnel filtering.
  - Clock-skew diagnostics, plaintext-token and revocation warnings.
- Binary checksum gate bumped to the v1.2.0 `buddynet-linux-amd64` sha256.

###2026.06.14.1
- Aligned with the buddy SAS / session model:
  - Runs `--no-interactive` (headless has no terminal to compare a first-contact
    SAS), so an unknown buddy key is refused, never learned blind.
  - The Buddy key (pin) is now effectively required — the page and service warn
    when it is missing, since the connection is refused without it.
  - Uses the legacy fixed-token mode (token + pinned buddy key), the right
    pattern for an unattended node; identity key, trust store and peer cache stay
    on the array.

###2026.06.14
- Initial BuddyNet Unraid client plugin, ported from the hardware-tested
  BuddyPeer plugin:
  - Settings page (Tools -&gt; BuddyNet) + boot/array-managed service running
    `buddynet --role=buddy`.
  - Bidirectional over one tunnel: -L (push to buddy) and -forward (receive).
  - Live status: buddy traffic-light, per-direction transfer + throughput.
  - Dashboard tile with a buddy online/offline traffic-light.
  - Binary verified against a pinned SHA256 on every install.
  - Secrets kept off the FAT flash: token file and the identity key + trust
    store + peer cache live on /mnt/user/appdata/buddynet/ (real 0600).
  - Danger zone: reset identity / forget buddy (shred where supported).
  - Clean uninstall removes config, identity, trust store and peer cache.

> **Maintainer note:** before publishing, set BINVER/BINURL/BINSHA in the
> install section below to a real `buddynet` release asset
> (`buddynet-linux-amd64`) and its sha256. Until then the checksum gate will
> (correctly) refuse to install.
</CHANGES>

