</div>

<script>
function bnShow(id,b){var e=document.getElementById(id);
  if(e.type==='password'){e.type='text';b.textContent='hide';}
  else{e.type='password';b.textContent='show';}}
// Generate a strong 384-bit token (64 base64url chars), same shape as the
// CLI's `buddynet gen-token`. Reveal it so it can be copied/shared.
function bnGen(id){var a=new Uint8Array(48);crypto.getRandomValues(a);
  var s=btoa(String.fromCharCode.apply(null,a)).replace(/\+/g,'-').replace(/\//g,'_');
  var e=document.getElementById(id);e.value=s;e.type='text';}
</script>

<form markdown="1" method="POST" action="/update.php" target="progressFrame">
<input type="hidden" name="#file" value="buddynet/buddynet.cfg">
<input type="hidden" name="#command" value="/etc/rc.d/rc.buddynet">
<input type="hidden" name="#arg[1]" value="restart">

Service:
: <select name="SERVICE">
  <option value="enable"  <?=v($cfg,'SERVICE')=='enable'?'selected':''?>>Enabled</option>
  <option value="disable" <?=v($cfg,'SERVICE')=='disable'?'selected':''?>>Disabled</option>
  </select>

Handshake server (host:port):
: <input type="text" name="SERVER" value="<?=v($cfg,'SERVER')?>" placeholder="vps.example:51820">

Server key (public pin — must match the server's identity):
: <input type="text" name="SERVER_KEY" value="<?=v($cfg,'SERVER_KEY')?>" placeholder="server Ed25519 public key, base64">

Token (shared secret — for testing; prefer the Token file below):
: <input type="password" id="bn_tok" name="TOKEN" value="<?=v($cfg,'TOKEN')?>"> <button type="button" onclick="bnShow('bn_tok',this)" style="align-self:flex-start;flex:0 0 auto;display:inline-block;width:auto;min-width:0;padding:1px 10px;margin-top:.2em">show</button> <button type="button" onclick="bnGen('bn_tok')" style="align-self:flex-start;flex:0 0 auto;display:inline-block;width:auto;min-width:0;padding:1px 10px;margin-top:.2em">generate</button>

Token file (on the array — overrides the field above, recommended):
: <input type="text" name="TOKEN_FILE" value="<?=v($cfg,'TOKEN_FILE')?>" placeholder="/mnt/user/appdata/buddynet/token (chmod 0600)">

Buddy key (public pin — your buddy's identity, **required headless**):
: <input type="text" name="PEER_KEY" value="<?=v($cfg,'PEER_KEY')?>" placeholder="buddy Ed25519 identity, base64">

Expose local port (-L) — to push backups TO your buddy:
: <input type="text" name="LISTEN" value="<?=v($cfg,'LISTEN')?>" placeholder="127.0.0.1:9000 (leave empty to disable)">

Forward to local service (-forward) — to receive backups FROM your buddy:
: <input type="text" name="FORWARD" value="<?=v($cfg,'FORWARD')?>" placeholder="127.0.0.1:873 (leave empty to disable)">

BuddyDNS name (--name) — reachable as &lt;name&gt;.buddy:
: <input type="text" name="NAME" value="<?=v($cfg,'NAME')?>" placeholder="alice (letters/digits/hyphens, max 63 — leave empty to disable)">

BuddyDNS resolver (--dns) — answer *.buddy on 127.0.0.153:53:
: <select name="DNS">
  <option value="disable" <?=v($cfg,'DNS')=='disable'?'selected':''?>>Disabled</option>
  <option value="enable"  <?=v($cfg,'DNS')=='enable'?'selected':''?>>Enabled</option>
  </select>

Lazy tunnel (--lazy) — defer the tunnel until the first -L connection (needs -L):
: <select name="LAZY">
  <option value="disable" <?=v($cfg,'LAZY')=='disable'?'selected':''?>>Disabled</option>
  <option value="enable"  <?=v($cfg,'LAZY')=='enable'?'selected':''?>>Enabled</option>
  </select>

WireGuard data plane (--wireguard) — carry the peer tunnel over kernel WireGuard instead of QUIC; the partner is reachable natively at its VIP (10.66.X.Y). Needs the Buddy key above pinned:
: <select name="WIREGUARD">
  <option value="disable" <?=v($cfg,'WIREGUARD')=='disable'?'selected':''?>>Disabled</option>
  <option value="enable"  <?=v($cfg,'WIREGUARD')=='enable'?'selected':''?>>Enabled</option>
  </select>

&nbsp;
: <input type="submit" value="Apply">

</form>

Set **both** addresses for back-and-forth backup over one tunnel: -L lets you
rsync to your buddy (`rsync://localhost:9000/...`), -forward lets your buddy
reach your local rsync daemon on :873. At least one is required.

**BuddyDNS** lets you reach your buddy by a name instead of a virtual IP. Set a
**name** (e.g. `alice` → your buddy reaches you as `alice.buddy`) and/or enable
the **resolver** so this host answers `*.buddy` queries on `127.0.0.153:53`. To
use the names on the Unraid host itself, route the `.buddy` TLD to that resolver
(see the project [BUDDYDNS.md](https://github.com/TZERO78/buddynet/blob/main/docs/BUDDYDNS.md)).
**Lazy tunnel** keeps the -L listener open but defers the encrypted tunnel until
the first connection actually arrives (needs -L set) — handy when a backup tool
connects only occasionally.

This node runs the **buddy** role. Its identity key, trust store and peer cache
live on the array under `/mnt/user/appdata/buddynet/`. Because Unraid runs the
buddy headless, there is no terminal to compare the first-contact **safety check
(SAS)** — so you **must pin your buddy** by entering its identity in the Buddy
key field above (the buddy prints its identity at startup, or run
`buddynet --role=handshake --key … identity` on the server for the server key).
Without a pin the connection is refused, never trusted blindly. See the project
README and SECURITY.md.

**Secret note:** the USB flash is FAT, so file permissions are not enforced there
— a Token typed above is effectively readable. For real protection put the token
in a file on the array (e.g. `/mnt/user/appdata/buddynet/token`, `chmod 0600`),
set "Token file" above and leave the Token field empty. The service then starts
on array start, once that file is available.

---
####Danger zone
<div style="display:flex;gap:1em;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-top:.5em">
<form method="POST" action="/update.php" target="progressFrame" style="margin:0"
      onsubmit="return confirm('Delete the trust store (known_peers)? The buddy key will be re-learned on the next connect (trust-on-first-use).');">
  <input type="hidden" name="#command" value="/etc/rc.d/rc.buddynet">
  <input type="hidden" name="#arg[1]" value="forget-buddy">
  <input type="submit" value="Forget buddy (clear known_peers)">
</form>
<form method="POST" action="/update.php" target="progressFrame" style="margin:0"
      onsubmit="return confirm('Really delete this node identity AND trust store? A NEW identity (and virtual IP) is generated on restart, so your buddy MUST re-pin your new Buddy key. This cannot be undone.');">
  <input type="hidden" name="#command" value="/etc/rc.d/rc.buddynet">
  <input type="hidden" name="#arg[1]" value="reset-identity">
  <input type="submit" value="Reset identity (delete id.key + known_peers)">
</form>
</div>

Keys are deleted with `shred` where supported. Note: on SSD/CoW filesystems a
secure overwrite is not guaranteed (wear-levelling), but the files are removed.
]]>
